=======================================================================================

An object array is a container that stores multiple objects in a single variable. You can think of it like a row of boxes, each holding an object.
Object[] arr = new Object[3];
arr[0] = "Mayur";
arr[1] = 101;
arr[2] = 8.75;

- Object[] can hold any type of object: String, Integer, Double, custom classes, etc.
- It cannot hold primitives directly (like int, double) — they get autoboxed into wrapper classes (Integer, Double, etc.).

for example
class Student {
    int rollNo;
    String name;
    double sgpa;

    Student(int r, String n, double s) {
        rollNo = r;
        name = n;
        sgpa = s;
    }
}

Student[] students = new Student[2];
students[0] = new Student(101, "Mayur", 8.75);
students[1] = new Student(102, "Asha", 9.10);

- To store heterogeneous data (with Object[])
- To store multiple instances of a class (like Student[])
- Useful in data structures, tables, or dynamic programming


========================================================================================

Everything in Java is built on other utility classes!
```

## Layers of Utility Classes
```
Scanner (easiest to use)
   ↓ uses
BufferedReader (medium difficulty)
   ↓ uses
InputStreamReader (more complex)
   ↓ uses
System.in (even more low-level)
   ↓ uses
Native system calls (operating system level)



When you write this
Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
You are creating an object — yes, exactly like any other Java object!

Scanner → is a class (a blueprint).
new Scanner(System.in) → creates a real object from that class, and stores it in heap memory.
sc → is just a reference variable that points to that object.

Memory:
┌─────────────┐
│ sc          │───►  [ Scanner object in heap ]
└─────────────┘

What’s inside that Scanner object
A buffer (a place in memory to hold keyboard input temporarily).
A connection (link) to System.in, which is Java’s built-in stream for keyboard input.

Keyboard → System.in → Scanner buffer → Your code

When you call methods like:
Here’s what happens behind the scenes:

Scanner looks at its buffer.

If it’s empty, it waits for you to type on the keyboard.

You type something and press Enter.

It reads that input, stores it in the buffer, and splits it into text (tokens).

Returns the text to your variable.

So yes — the Scanner object is doing real work every time you call its methods.

