//informative
class ArrStack {
    int[] stack;  stack  --->  null
    int head = -1;
    
    ArrStack(int len) {
        stack = new int[len]; stack  --->  [ 0, 0, 0, 0, 0 ]   // an array of length = len

    }
}

--------------------------------------------------------
//public, private and default keywords in java

public
Accessible from any other class or package in the Java program.
Typically used for methods or variables that need to be available globally.

private
Accessible only within the class where it is declared.
Used to restrict access and encapsulate data, protecting it from external modification.

-------------------------------------------------------
//Static and non static Variables.

Static variable -

static int = 5;
Memory is allocated only once when the class is loaded
All instances of the class share the same static variable.
Can be accessed using the class name (e.g., ClassName.variableName), and also by object reference—but class name is preferred.
Commonly used for constants, counters, or to store information shared across all objects.


Non Static Variables

Memory is allocated every time an object is created.



